## 5. Key Concepts Used

### 5.1 Hyperledger Fabric — Permissioned Blockchain

Unlike public blockchains (Bitcoin, Ethereum), Hyperledger Fabric is a **permissioned** blockchain where:
- All participants have **known identities** (via X.509 certificates).
- Only authorized organizations can join the network.
- **No cryptocurrency or mining** — consensus is achieved through an ordering service.
- The ledger is private to the network participants.

> [!NOTE]
> This makes Fabric ideal for government-level applications like e-voting, where participant identity verification is mandatory.

### 5.2 Smart Contracts (Chaincode)

The business logic of the voting system lives in a **chaincode** — a Node.js smart contract deployed to the Fabric peer nodes. It defines:
- What data can be stored on the blockchain (constituencies, voters, candidates, votes)
- What operations are allowed (create, register, vote, query)
- What validations are enforced (duplicate checks, phase checks, constituency matching)

### 5.3 Fabric Network Components

| Component | Role |
|-----------|------|
| **Peer Node** (`peer0.org1`) | Hosts the chaincode, maintains a copy of the ledger, endorses transactions |
| **Orderer** (`orderer.example.com`) | Orders transactions into blocks, ensures consistency across peers |
| **Certificate Authority** (`ca.org1`) | Issues X.509 digital certificates for identity management |
| **Channel** (`mychannel`) | A private communication sub-network; all voting data lives on this channel |

### 5.4 SHA-256 Hashing for Voter Privacy

Voter EPIC (Electors Photo Identity Card) numbers are **never stored in plaintext** on the blockchain. Instead, the chaincode hashes the EPIC number using **SHA-256** before storing it:

```javascript
_hashEPIC(epicNumber) {
    return crypto.createHash('sha256')
        .update(epicNumber)
        .digest('hex');
}
```

This ensures **voter privacy** — even if the ledger is inspected, real voter identities remain protected.

### 5.5 Membership Service Provider (MSP)

Every operation on the blockchain is tied to an **MSP identity**. The chaincode enforces that only **Org1MSP** (representing the Election Commission) can:
- Create constituencies
- Register voters and candidates
- Start and end elections

```javascript
_requireMSP(ctx, "Org1MSP", "Only Election Commission can perform this action");
```

### 5.6 Transaction Types

| Type | SDK Method | Description |
|------|-----------|-------------|
| **Submit** (Write) | `contract.submitTransaction()` | Writes to the ledger; requires endorsement and ordering (consensus) |
| **Evaluate** (Read) | `contract.evaluateTransaction()` | Reads from the local ledger copy; no consensus required; fast |

### 5.7 Election Lifecycle (State Machine)

```mermaid
stateDiagram-v2
    [*] --> CREATED : createConstituency()
    CREATED --> VOTING : startElection()
    VOTING --> CLOSED : endElection()
    CLOSED --> [*]

    note right of CREATED : Candidates & voters\ncan be registered
    note right of VOTING : Votes can be cast
    note right of CLOSED : Results are final\nNo more votes
```

### 5.8 Deterministic Timestamps

The chaincode uses the **transaction timestamp** from the blockchain (not `Date.now()`) to ensure all peers agree on the same timestamp for a vote:

```javascript
_getDeterministicTimestamp(ctx) {
    const txTime = ctx.stub.getTxTimestamp();
    const seconds = txTime.seconds.low;
    const nanos = txTime.nanos;
    return new Date(seconds * 1000 + nanos / 1000000).toISOString();
}
```

### 5.9 Connection Profile & Wallet

- **Connection Profile** (`connection-org1.json`): A JSON file containing the network topology — peer URLs, orderer URLs, TLS certificates, and CA information. Generated dynamically by reading certs from the running Fabric network.
- **Wallet** (`./wallet/`): A directory storing enrolled admin X.509 certificates and private keys. The backend uses these to authenticate with the Fabric network.

